	"conclusion": "For Notion, the career page partially precedes Linkedin: 22% of matched jobs (10/45) appeared on the career page first, with an average lead of 119 days (median: 43 days). An additional 106 jobs (70% of career-page listings) were never indexed by Linkedin at all. This confirms that the career page is the primary source of truth for job postings.",
	"geminiSummary": "Analysis of 45 matched job postings reveals that company career pages indeed precede LinkedIn for a significant portion, though not all, new roles. In 10 instances (22%) of matched jobs, the career page published the opening first, preceding LinkedIn by an average of 119 days and a median of 43 days. Conversely, LinkedIn posted first for 32 matched jobs, while 3 jobs appeared on both platforms on the same day. Furthermore, a substantial 106 unique jobs were found exclusively on career pages during the analysis period, never appearing on LinkedIn.\n\nThe detailed lag distribution provides a clearer picture for job seekers. While the average lag is influenced by extreme outliers like \"Account Executive, Mid-Market\" (632 days ahead), a more common pattern emerges from the distribution: two jobs appeared on career pages 1-3 days earlier, two jobs 15-30 days earlier, and another two jobs 31-60 days earlier. This indicates that while dramatic leads of several months are possible for a few roles, a more frequent advantage lies within the 1-60 day window, allowing early applicants to potentially engage with a role weeks before it becomes widely visible.\n\nIt is crucial to acknowledge several data limitations that may influence these observations. The significantly higher frequency of career page snapshots (200) compared to LinkedIn snapshots (6) over the 28-month analysis period (2024-01-01 to 2026-04-01) could potentially skew the perceived lag. A less frequent LinkedIn crawl coverage might lead to an overestimation of the delay in LinkedIn postings, as an earlier post might have been missed. Similarly, the CDX snapshot frequency, though higher for career pages, inherently limits the precision of \"first seen\" dates. These factors suggest that the actual lags could be somewhat shorter than observed, especially for LinkedIn-first scenarios.\n\nFor job seekers aiming to gain a competitive edge, the data strongly suggests a strategic advantage in regularly monitoring company career pages directly. This proactive approach could offer access to roles anywhere from a few days to several weeks, or even months, before they are published on broader platforms like LinkedIn. Focusing on career pages directly provides an opportunity to be among the earliest applicants, particularly for roles that might never reach LinkedIn or for those where a tangible early advantage of 1-60 days is observed.",
	"geminiAvailable": true
